    <title type="html"><![CDATA[Dynamic DNS Updater for CloudFlare]]></title>
    <link href="http://carmo.org.uk/cloudflare-dynamicdns-updater-raspberry-pi/"/>
    <updated>2013-03-24T19:42:00+00:00</updated>
    <id>http://carmo.org.uk/cloudflare-dynamicdns-updater-raspberry-pi</id>
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p>Over the weekend I decided to move hosting of this blog from Github Pages to the Raspberry Pi that resides in the bedroom of my home<sup id='fnref:1'><a href='#fn:1' rel='footnote'>1</a></sup>. The site has always been protected by the impressive <a href="http://www.cloudflare.com/">CloudFlare</a> but that protection is even more critical now I&#8217;ve made that change, it does however present a particular challenge around dynamically assigned IP addresses that ISP&#8217;s dish out on consumer broadband and fibre networks.</p>

<center><img src="https://dl.dropbox.com/u/22370970/blogimages/cloudflare.png"></center>


<p>CloudFlare needs to be kept informed of the currently assigned IP address that the Pi is sitting behind and although they do offer an API and <a href="http://robertianhawdon.me.uk/2012/07/17/fixing-ddclient-to-work-with-cloudflare/">a dyndns client</a>, it&#8217;s a little troublesome to get working so I decided the best approach would be a simple bash script.</p>

<div><script src='https://gist.github.com/5252855.js'></script>
<noscript><pre><code></code></pre></noscript></div>


<p>The script runs perfectly on a Raspberry Pi and all it needs is a simple alteration to include your own domain, CloudFlare Username and API key, then add it to a cron job and it will keep your CloudFlare DNS up to date with the currently assigned dynamic IP at an interval of your choosing<sup id='fnref:2'><a href='#fn:2' rel='footnote'>2</a></sup>.</p>

<p>Any support, issues, comments or feedback are always welcome by getting in touch on <a href="http://twitter.com/macjasp">Twitter</a>.</p>

<br>


<br>


<div class="footnotes">
    <ol>
        <li id='fn:1'><p><del>The static pages of this Octopress blog are being served by <a href="http://nginx.org/en/">Nginx</a> and performance is admirable on the Raspberry Pi</del> I&#8217;ve since had to move hosting back to Github Pages following some weird sleeping issues the Pi was experiencing.
<a href='#fnref:1' rev='footnote'>↩</a></p>
</li><li id='fn:2'><p>I currently have mine set to update CloudFlare every 55 minutes.
<a href='#fnref:2' rev='footnote'>↩</a></p>
</li>
    </ol>
</div>

]]></content>
